07981nam a22007935i 9780822387992DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223879927 a10.1515/97808223879922doi  a(DE-B1597)554054  a(OCoLC)1136208776  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF970b.H26 2006 7aHIS0360002bisacsh00aHaunted by Empire :bGeographies of Intimacy in North American History /cAnn Laura Stoler, Emily S. Rosenberg, Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (568 p.) :b6 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntimidations of Empire: Predicaments of the Tactile and Unseen -- tTense and Tender Ties: The Politics of Comparison in North American History and (Post) Colonial Studies -- tConvergence and Comparison -- tSamoa's Half-Castes and Some Frontiers of Comparison -- tStates of Hygiene: Race ''Improvement'' and Biomedical Citizenship in Australia and the Colonial Philippines -- tAdjudicating Intimacies on U.S. Frontiers -- tProper Caresses and Prudent Distance: A How-To Manual from Colonial Louisiana -- t''His Kingdom for a Kiss'': Indians and Intimacy in the Narrative of John Marrant -- tProximities of Power -- tThe Intimacies of Four Continents -- tBody Work in the Antebellum United States -- tFractions and Fictions in the United States Census of 1890 -- tThe Fair Ensemble: Kate Chopin in St. Louis in 1904 -- t''The Perfect Mistress of Russian Economy'': Sighting the Intimate on a Colonial Alaskan Terrain, 1784-182 -- tCircuits of Knowledge Production -- tAn Empire of Tests: Psychometrics and the Paradoxes of Nationalism in the Americas -- tMaking ''American'' Families: Transnational Adoption and U.S. Latin America Policy -- tThe Darkness That Enters the Home: The Politics of Prostitution during the Philippine-American War -- tOrdering Others: U.S. Financial Advisers in the Early Twentieth Century -- tRefractions -- tInternal Colonialism and Gender -- tCommentary -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA milestone in U.S. historiography, Haunted by Empire brings postcolonial critiques to bear on North American history and draws on that history to question the analytic conventions of postcolonial studies. The contributors to this innovative collection examine the critical role of "domains of the intimate" in the consolidation of colonial power. They demonstrate how the categories of difference underlying colonialism-the distinctions advanced as the justification for the colonizer's rule of the colonized-were enacted and reinforced in intimate realms from the bedroom to the classroom to the medical examining room. Together the essays focus attention on the politics of comparison-on how colonizers differentiated one group or set of behaviors from another-and on the circulation of knowledge and ideologies within and between imperial projects. Ultimately, this collection forces a rethinking of what historians choose to compare and of the epistemological grounds on which those choices are based.Haunted by Empire includes Ann Laura Stoler's seminal essay "Tense and Tender Ties" as well as her bold introduction, which carves out the exciting new analytic and methodological ground animated by this comparative venture. The contributors engage in a lively cross-disciplinary conversation, drawing on history, anthropology, literature, philosophy, and public health. They address such topics as the regulation of Hindu marriages and gay sexuality in the early-twentieth-century United States; the framing of multiple-choice intelligence tests; the deeply entangled histories of Asian, African, and native peoples in the Americas; the racial categorizations used in the 1890 U.S. census; and the politics of race and space in French colonial New Orleans. Linda Gordon, Catherine Hall, and Nancy F. Cott each provide a concluding essay reflecting on the innovations and implications of the arguments advanced in Haunted by Empire.Contributors. Warwick Anderson, Laura Briggs, Kathleen Brown, Nancy F. Cott, Shannon Lee Dawdy, Linda Gordon, Catherine Hall, Martha Hodes, Paul A. Kramer, Lisa Lowe, Tiya Miles, Gwenn A. Miller, Emily S. Rosenberg, Damon Salesa, Nayan Shah, Alexandra Minna Stern, Ann Laura Stoler, Laura Wexler  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aIntimacy (Psychology)xPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIntimacy (Psychology)xSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aStern, Alexandra Minna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStoler, Ann Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalesa, Damon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Emily S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Gwenn A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriggs, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWexler, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLowe, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodes, Ma